I could've sworn
they were in my jacket
before I got on.

41
00:03:22,785 --> 00:03:25,371
Government employees
will rob you blind.

42
00:03:28,157 --> 00:03:30,376
Thanks.

43
00:03:30,376 --> 00:03:33,213
They give you a briefing
about the institution
before you left?

44
00:03:33,213 --> 00:03:35,632
All I know is it's
a mental hospital.

45
00:03:36,633 --> 00:03:38,134
For the criminally insane.

46
00:03:38,134 --> 00:03:39,636
(CHUCKLES)

47
00:03:39,636 --> 00:03:42,138
Well, if it's just
folks running around
hearing voices

48
00:03:42,138 --> 00:03:45,475
and chasing
after butterflies,
they wouldn't need us.

49
00:03:54,400 --> 00:03:56,236
Is that where
we're headed?

50
00:03:56,236 --> 00:03:57,737
Yep.

51
00:03:57,737 --> 00:04:00,240
The other side
of the island
is rock bluffs

52
00:04:00,240 --> 00:04:02,742
all the way down
to the edge
of the water.

53
00:04:03,243 --> 00:04:07,530
The dock,
it's the only way
on or off.

54
00:04:07,530 --> 00:04:10,333
We'll be casting off
as soon as you two
are ashore.

55
00:04:10,833 --> 00:04:13,086
I'd appreciate it if
you'd hurry up about it.

56
00:04:13,586 --> 00:04:14,337
Why?

57
00:04:14,337 --> 00:04:16,039
Storm's coming.

58
00:04:42,699 --> 00:04:45,034
Never seen
a Marshals badge before.

59
00:04:46,786 --> 00:04:48,621
I'm Deputy Warden McPherson,
gentlemen.

60
00:04:48,621 --> 00:04:50,123
Welcome to Shutter Island.

61
00:04:50,123 --> 00:04:53,209
I'll be the one taking you
up to Ashecliffe.

62
00:05:05,254 --> 00:05:08,257
Your boys seem
a little on edge,
Mr. McPherson.

63
00:05:08,257 --> 00:05:10,760
Right now, Marshal,
we all are.

64
00:05:54,721 --> 00:05:56,723
Electrified perimeter.

65
00:05:58,725 --> 00:06:00,727
How can you tell?

66
00:06:00,727 --> 00:06:03,229
I've seen somethin
g like it before.

67
00:06:32,225 --> 00:06:33,726
All right.

68
00:06:33,726 --> 00:06:35,728
You gentlemen will be
accorded all the help
we can give,

69
00:06:36,229 --> 00:06:38,731
.
but during your stay,
you will obey protocol

70
00:06:39,232 --> 00:06:40,400
Is that understood?

71
00:06:40,400 --> 00:06:42,185
Absolutely.

72
00:06:42,185 --> 00:06:45,855
The red brick building
on your right is Ward A,
the male ward.

73
00:06:45,855 --> 00:06:49,192
Ward B, the female ward,
is the one on your left.

74
00:06:49,192 --> 00:06:52,195
Ward C is that building
on the bluffs.

75
00:06:52,195 --> 00:06:54,030
An old Civil War fort.

76
00:06:54,030 --> 00:06:56,332
The most dangerous patient
s are housed there.

77
00:06:56,332 --> 00:06:58,334
Admittance to
Ward C is forbidden

78
00:06:58,334 --> 00:07:01,337
without the written consent 
and physical presence

79
00:07:01,337 --> 00:07:03,840
of both myself
and Dr. Cawley.

80
00:07:03,840 --> 00:07:06,426
Is that understood?

81
00:07:06,426 --> 00:07:09,212
You act like
insanity is catching.

82
00:07:12,048 --> 00:07:15,301
.
You are hereby required
to surrender your firearms

83
00:07:16,803 --> 00:07:19,806
Mr. McPherson,
we are duly appointed
federal marshals.

84
00:07:19,806 --> 00:07:22,809
We are required to
carry our firearms
with us at all times.

85
00:07:22,809 --> 00:07:25,478
Executive order 319
of the Federal Code
of Penitentiaries

86
00:07:25,978 --> 00:07:27,897
states that when
inside a penitentiary,

87
00:07:27,897 --> 00:07:31,400
the officers of
that institution
have final authority.

88
00:07:34,070 --> 00:07:37,957
Gentlemen, you will not
get through this gate
with your firearms.

89
00:07:57,510 --> 00:08:00,930
Okay. Now that
the official stuff's done,
come on, boys,

90
00:08:00,930 --> 00:08:02,815
what do you say
we go find Dr. Cawley?

91
00:08:15,027 --> 00:08:17,530
When did she escape?
This prisoner?

92
00:08:18,030 --> 00:08:19,532
I'm afraid Dr. Cawley
will have to fill you in

93
00:08:19,532 --> 00:08:22,034
on the situation.
Protocol.

94
00:08:22,034 --> 00:08:24,036
Correctional officers
at a mental institution,

95
00:08:24,036 --> 00:08:26,422
that's a weird sight,
if you don't
mind me saying.

96
00:08:26,422 --> 00:08:28,875
McPHERSON:
It's the only facility
of its kind in the U.S.,

97
00:08:28,875 --> 00:08:30,376
even the world.

98
00:08:30,376 --> 00:08:32,378
We take only
the most dangerous,
damaged patients,

99
00:08:32,879 --> 00:08:34,380
ones no other
hospital can manage.

100
00:08:34,380 --> 00:08:36,599
And it's all
due to Dr. Cawley.

101
00:08:36,599 --> 00:08:38,518
He's created something
really unique here.

102
00:08:38,518 --> 00:08:40,520
It's a hospital for
people our society

103
00:08:40,520 --> 00:08:42,221
normally considers
beyond treatment.

104
00:09:07,079 --> 00:09:09,165
Top of his class
at Johns Hopkins,
then Harvard...

105
00:09:09,165 --> 00:09:10,333
(BUZZER RINGS)

106
00:09:10,333 --> 00:09:11,968
IDs, gentlemen.

107
00:09:15,304 --> 00:09:17,840
Show your badges, gentlemen.

108
00:09:17,840 --> 00:09:21,510
Dr. Cawley's been consulted 
numerous times by Scotland Yard,

109
00:09:21,510 --> 00:09:23,396
MI5, the OSS...

110
00:09:23,396 --> 00:09:25,398
Why?

111
00:09:25,398 --> 00:09:26,899
What do you mean?

112
00:09:28,234 --> 00:09:29,735
What do intelligence agencies

113
00:09:29,735 --> 00:09:31,604
want to consult
a psychiatrist about?

114
00:09:31,604 --> 00:09:33,606
I guess you'll have to ask him.

115
00:09:34,523 --> 00:09:35,858
(BUZZER RINGS)

116
00:09:43,499 --> 00:09:44,500
Marshal Daniels.

117
00:09:45,001 --> 00:09:46,002
.
Doctor

118
00:09:46,002 --> 00:09:48,254
Marshal Aule.

119
00:09:48,254 --> 00:09:51,123
Thank you, Deputy Warden.
That will be all.

120
00:09:51,123 --> 00:09:53,626
Yes, sir.
Pleasure, gentlemen.

121
00:09:55,628 --> 00:09:56,929
He had a lot to say about you.

122
00:09:56,929 --> 00:10:00,349
McPherson's a good man.
He believes in
the work we do here.

123
00:10:00,349 --> 00:10:02,802
And what would
that be, exactly?

124
00:10:02,802 --> 00:10:06,355
A moral fusion
between law and order
and clinical care.

125
00:10:06,355 --> 00:10:09,558
CHUCK: Pardon me, Doc.
A what between
what and what?

126
00:10:16,732 --> 00:10:19,735
Those paintings
are quite accurate.

127
00:10:19,735 --> 00:10:21,737
Used to be the kind of patients
we deal with here

128
00:10:21,737 --> 00:10:24,740
were shackled and left
in their own filth.

129
00:10:24,740 --> 00:10:26,242
They were beaten,

130
00:10:26,242 --> 00:10:28,494
as if whipping them bloody
would drive the psychosis out.

131
00:10:28,494 --> 00:10:30,630
We drove screws into their brains,

132
00:10:30,630 --> 00:10:34,634
we submerged them
in icy water until
they lost consciousness.

133
00:10:35,635 --> 00:10:37,136
or even drowned.

134
00:10:37,136 --> 00:10:39,088
And now?
We treat them.

135
00:10:39,088 --> 00:10:41,590
Try to heal,
try to cure.

136
00:10:41,590 --> 00:10:43,092
And if that fails,
at least we provide them

137
00:10:43,592 --> 00:10:46,479
with a measure of comfort
in their lives. Calm.

138
00:10:46,479 --> 00:10:49,849
These are all violent offenders,
right?

139
00:10:49,849 --> 00:10:51,984
I mean, they've hurt people.

140
00:10:52,985 --> 00:10:54,320
Murdered them in some cases.

141
00:10:54,320 --> 00:10:56,822
In almost all cases, yes.

142
00:10:56,822 --> 00:10:58,824
Then, personally, Doctor,
I'd have to say,

143
00:10:58,824 --> 00:11:01,327
screw their sense of calm.

144
00:11:02,862 --> 00:11:05,031
It's my job to treat my patients,
not their victims.

145
00:11:05,031 --> 00:11:06,699
I'm not here to judge.

146
00:11:06,699 --> 00:11:08,534
So this female prisoner...

147
00:11:08,534 --> 00:11:10,036
Patient.

148
00:11:10,036 --> 00:11:12,121
Excuse me. Patient,

149
00:11:12,121 --> 00:11:17,293
one Rachel Solando, escaped 
sometime in the last 24 hours.

150
00:11:17,293 --> 00:11:19,628
.
Last night between
10:00 and midnight

151
00:11:19,628 --> 00:11:21,013
Is she considered dangerous?

152
00:11:21,013 --> 00:11:25,434
You could say that.
She killed all three
of her children.

153
00:11:25,935 --> 00:11:28,804
She drowned them
in the lake behind her house.

154
00:11:28,804 --> 00:11:29,605
She took them out
one by one,

155
00:11:30,022 --> 00:11:31,891
held their heads
under till they died,

156
00:11:31,891 --> 00:11:33,392
then she brought
them back inside

157
00:11:33,392 --> 00:11:34,894
and arranged them
around the kitchen table.

158
00:11:34,894 --> 00:11:38,230
She ate a meal there before 
a neighbor dropped by.

159
00:11:40,232 --> 00:11:41,734
And what about
the husband?

160
00:11:41,734 --> 00:11:45,705
He died on the beaches of 
Normandy. She's a war widow.

161
00:11:46,205 --> 00:11:48,074
She starved herself
when she first came here.

162
00:11:48,574 --> 00:11:51,210
She insisted
the children weren't dead.

163
00:11:56,582 --> 00:11:58,134
(DISTORTED CHATTER)

164
00:12:01,053 --> 00:12:03,556
Sorry, Doctor.
You don't happen to have
an aspirin, do you?

165
00:12:04,056 --> 00:12:05,591
Prone to headaches,
Marshal?

166
00:12:05,591 --> 00:12:09,061
Sometimes. But today,
I'm a little more
prone to seasickness.

167
00:12:09,061 --> 00:12:10,563
Ah, dehydration.

168
00:12:11,063 --> 00:12:12,732
You all right, boss?
Yeah.

169
00:12:12,732 --> 00:12:15,234
In that case,
you're quite right.
The simpler the better.

170
00:12:15,234 --> 00:12:17,570
Thanks so much.

171
00:12:18,020 --> 00:12:21,524
Rachel still believes
the children are alive.

172
00:12:21,524 --> 00:12:24,276
She also believes
this place is her home
in the Berkshires.

173
00:12:24,610 --> 00:12:25,611
(CHUCKLES)

174
00:12:26,612 --> 00:12:27,613
You're kidding me.

175
00:12:27,613 --> 00:12:28,614
She's never once
in two years

176
00:12:29,031 --> 00:12:30,533
acknowledged that
she's in an institution.

177
00:12:30,533 --> 00:12:34,420
She believes
we're all deliverymen,
milkmen, postal workers.

178
00:12:34,420 --> 00:12:36,622
To sustain the delusion
that her children never died,

179
00:12:37,123 --> 00:12:39,125
she's created an elaborate
fictional structure,

180
00:12:39,125 --> 00:12:43,379
and she gives us all
parts to play in that fiction.

181
00:12:43,379 --> 00:12:45,264
So have you searched
the grounds yet?

182
00:12:45,264 --> 00:12:47,767
The warden and his men
scoured the island.

183
00:12:48,267 --> 00:12:50,352
Not a trace.

184
00:12:50,352 --> 00:12:51,270
And what's more
disturbing is

185
00:12:51,270 --> 00:12:54,774
we don't know how she got out
of her room.

186
00:12:54,774 --> 00:12:57,276
It was locked from the outside,

187
00:12:57,276 --> 00:12:58,778
and the only window is barred.

188
00:13:01,697 --> 00:13:04,700
It's as if she evaporated
straight through the walls.

189
00:13:10,790 --> 00:13:14,794
I brought her right back
here after group therapy,
locked her in,

190
00:13:14,794 --> 00:13:17,797
came back for midnight rounds,
she was gone.

191
00:13:24,470 --> 00:13:26,222
Seriously, Doctor,
how is it possible

192
00:13:26,722 --> 00:13:28,841
that the truth never
gets through to her?

193
00:13:28,841 --> 00:13:31,644
I mean, she's in a mental
institution, right?

194
00:13:31,644 --> 00:13:33,646
Seems like something you'd notice
from time to time.

195
00:13:34,146 --> 00:13:36,098
How many pairs of shoes are 
the patients given?

196
00:13:36,098 --> 00:13:37,433
Two pairs.

197
00:13:37,433 --> 00:13:39,401
Sanity's not a choice, Marshal.

198
00:13:39,902 --> 00:13:42,605
You can't just choose
to get over it.

199
00:13:42,605 --> 00:13:46,442
So, she left here barefoot?

200
00:13:46,442 --> 00:13:49,078
Come on, Doc, she couldn't get 
10 yards in that terrain.

201
00:13:50,579 --> 00:13:51,831
CAWLEY: Marshal?

202
00:14:11,133 --> 00:14:13,052
This is definitely
Rachel's handwriting.

203
00:14:13,052 --> 00:14:15,804
I have no idea what the law of
four is, though.

204
00:14:16,105 --> 00:14:17,606
It's not a psychiatric term?

205
00:14:17,606 --> 00:14:18,557
I'm afraid not.

206
00:14:19,058 --> 00:14:20,559
"Who is 67?"

207
00:14:21,560 --> 00:14:23,062
.
Fuck if I know

208
00:14:23,062 --> 00:14:26,398
.
I have to say
that's quite close to
my clinical conclusion

209
00:14:26,899 --> 00:14:28,400
Think it's just random scribblings?

210
00:14:28,868 --> 00:14:32,238
Oh, no, not at all.
Rachel's smart. Brilliant, in fact.

211
00:14:32,738 --> 00:14:34,156
This paper could be important.

212
00:14:34,156 --> 00:14:37,159
Excuse me, Doctor,
but we're gonna have
to hold on to this.

213
00:14:37,159 --> 00:14:38,494
Of course.

214
00:14:40,412 --> 00:14:43,415
CHUCK: And you say
she had to come
through here?

215
00:14:43,415 --> 00:14:47,419
.
After lights out, the orderlies
play cards in here

216
00:14:47,419 --> 00:14:49,421
Last night,
there were seven men

217
00:14:49,421 --> 00:14:50,756
sitting at the base of those stairs

218
00:14:51,173 --> 00:14:52,675
playing stud poker.

219
00:14:52,675 --> 00:14:55,511
Yet somehow, Rachel managed
to slip past them.

220
00:14:56,228 --> 00:14:57,346
(ANGUISHED) Why?

221
00:14:57,346 --> 00:15:00,683
How? She turns invisible?

222
00:15:00,683 --> 00:15:03,185
Doctor,
we're gonna need access
to the personnel files

223
00:15:03,185 --> 00:15:04,570
of all the medical staff.

224
00:15:04,937 --> 00:15:06,822
The nurses,
the guards, the orderlies,
anyone who was working then.

225
00:15:07,273 --> 00:15:09,108
We'll take your request under consideration.

226
00:15:09,108 --> 00:15:10,075
(CHUCKLES)

227
00:15:10,075 --> 00:15:12,578
This is not a request, Doctor.

228
00:15:12,578 --> 00:15:14,947
This is a federal facility,
and a dangerous prisoner...

229
00:15:15,414 --> 00:15:16,115
Patient.

230
00:15:16,615 --> 00:15:17,616
...patient

231
00:15:17,616 --> 00:15:19,952
has escaped.
Now, you will comply or...

232
00:15:19,952 --> 00:15:22,421
.
All I can say is
I'll see what I can do

233
00:15:22,421 --> 00:15:24,924
Doctor, we're gonna need to speak
with the staff.

234
00:15:25,424 --> 00:15:27,376
Do you understand?

235
00:15:27,376 --> 00:15:30,462
I'll assemble them in the common room
after dinner.

236
00:15:30,963 --> 00:15:32,464
If you have any further questions,

237
00:15:32,464 --> 00:15:35,467
feel free to join the deputy warden
in the search.

238
00:15:48,030 --> 00:15:49,281
McPHERSON: It's 11 miles
to the nearest land

239
00:15:49,281 --> 00:15:51,150
and the water's freezing.

240
00:15:51,150 --> 00:15:54,153
Current was strong last night,
tide pushing in.

241
00:15:54,153 --> 00:15:56,155
She'd have drowned
or been crushed on the rocks,

242
00:15:56,155 --> 00:15:59,158
and her body would have
washed back up on shore.

243
00:16:02,161 --> 00:16:03,462
TEDDY: What about
those caves down there?

244
00:16:03,462 --> 00:16:05,381
Have you checked them?

245
00:16:05,381 --> 00:16:07,883
No way she could get there.

246
00:16:07,883 --> 00:16:10,803
The bases of those cliffs
are covered in poison ivy,

247
00:16:10,803 --> 00:16:12,137
live oak, sumac,

248
00:16:12,137 --> 00:16:15,591
a thousand plants with thorns as big
as my dick.

249
00:16:15,591 --> 00:16:18,594
You said yourself, Marshal, she's got no shoes.

250
00:16:24,099 --> 00:16:26,902
All right, let's check
the other side.

251
00:16:32,024 --> 00:16:33,525
What's that tower?

252
00:16:34,026 --> 00:16:35,527
.
It's an old lighthouse

253
00:16:36,028 --> 00:16:38,530
.
The guards already
searched inside it

254
00:16:40,532 --> 00:16:42,534
What's in there?
More patients?

255
00:16:43,035 --> 00:16:45,537
Sewage treatment facility.

256
00:16:45,537 --> 00:16:49,291
It's getting dark soon . I'm calling this off
for tonight.

257
00:16:49,591 --> 00:16:51,093
Let's go, boys!

258
00:16:54,680 --> 00:16:56,682
TEDDY: You were on watch
on the landing, huh?

259
00:16:56,682 --> 00:16:58,634
Yeah. Couldn't nobody
get in or out

260
00:16:58,634 --> 00:17:00,135
of their room on that corridor

261
00:17:00,135 --> 00:17:01,887
without me seeing.

262
00:17:02,271 --> 00:17:03,972
Okay, Rachel Solando,

263
00:17:03,972 --> 00:17:06,975
who else does she have to pass
to get down here?

264
00:17:12,981 --> 00:17:15,818
Me. Glen Miga.

265
00:17:17,069 --> 00:17:19,071
Sir, I didn't see nothing.

266
00:17:19,071 --> 00:17:21,290
And you were at your post all night?

267
00:17:21,290 --> 00:17:23,575
Yeah, but I didn't see a thing.

268
00:17:25,461 --> 00:17:26,879
Glen.

269
00:17:28,130 --> 00:17:29,631
(INSISTENTLY) Glen.

270
00:17:32,468 --> 00:17:34,253
Tell me the truth.

271
00:17:35,254 --> 00:17:36,255
I...

272
00:17:38,340 --> 00:17:41,260
I maybe went to the bathroom.

273
00:17:41,510 --> 00:17:44,063
What? You breached protocol.
Christ...

274
00:17:44,063 --> 00:17:46,648
I wasn't gone more than a minute.

275
00:17:46,648 --> 00:17:49,435
All right, look. Let's back up here.
Let's all just back up

276
00:17:49,435 --> 00:17:52,938
Miss Solando was put in her room
for lights out.

277
00:17:52,938 --> 00:17:56,442
Does anyone here know
what she did before that?

278
00:17:56,442 --> 00:17:58,694
Anyone?

279
00:17:58,694 --> 00:18:01,697
(SNAPPING FINGERS)
Come on, anyone, anyone,
anyone, anyone.

280
00:18:01,697 --> 00:18:04,166
She was in a group therapy session.

281
00:18:04,166 --> 00:18:07,169
Huh.
Anything unusual occur?

282
00:18:08,087 --> 00:18:10,038
Define "unusual."

283
00:18:10,539 --> 00:18:11,540
Excuse me?

284
00:18:11,540 --> 00:18:13,709
This is a mental institution, Marshal,

285
00:18:13,709 --> 00:18:16,211
for the criminally insane.

286
00:18:16,211 --> 00:18:18,213
Usual isn't a big part of our day.

287
00:18:18,213 --> 00:18:19,765
(STAFF CHUCKLING)

288
00:18:20,265 --> 00:18:21,767
I will rephrase.

289
00:18:21,767 --> 00:18:23,268
Did anything happen last night

290
00:18:23,268 --> 00:18:25,771
during group therapy
that was more,

291
00:18:25,771 --> 00:18:28,273
let's say, I don't know,
memorable than...

292
00:18:28,273 --> 00:18:30,192
Normal?
Exactly.

293
00:18:30,692 --> 00:18:32,728
No. Sorry.

294
00:18:32,728 --> 00:18:36,031
Did Miss Solando say anything 
during group therapy?

295
00:18:36,899 --> 00:18:39,201
She was worried about the rain.

296
00:18:40,202 --> 00:18:42,037
And she hated the food here.

297
00:18:42,037 --> 00:18:44,039
(STAFF LAUGHING)
Complained constantly,

298
00:18:44,039 --> 00:18:45,824
last night included.

299
00:18:47,326 --> 00:18:50,913
So you were there. Was there a 
doctor present?

300
00:18:50,913 --> 00:18:53,665
Yes, Dr. Sheehan led the discussion.

301
00:18:54,550 --> 00:18:56,835
Dr. Sheehan?

302
00:18:56,835 --> 00:18:59,087
Yes, he was running the session.

303
00:19:00,672 --> 00:19:02,057
He's Rachel's primary,

304
00:19:02,057 --> 00:19:04,393
the psychiatrist who directly
oversees her care.

305
00:19:04,810 --> 00:19:05,811
Huh.

306
00:19:07,513 --> 00:19:09,348
We're gonna need
to speak with Dr. Sheehan.

307
00:19:09,765 --> 00:19:12,267
I'm afraid that won't be possible.

308
00:19:12,267 --> 00:19:14,269
He left on the ferry this morning.

309
00:19:14,269 --> 00:19:15,571
His vacation was already planned.

310
00:19:15,571 --> 00:19:17,439
He'd been putting it off too long.

311
00:19:17,439 --> 00:19:19,942
You're in a state of lockdown,

312
00:19:19,942 --> 00:19:22,444
a dangerous patient has escaped,

313
00:19:22,444 --> 00:19:27,449
and you let her primary doctor
leave on vacation?

314
00:19:27,449 --> 00:19:28,951
Well, of course. He's a doctor.

315
00:19:29,334 --> 00:19:30,702
(STAFF LAUGHING)

316
00:19:33,705 --> 00:19:37,709
Do you have the phone number
for where he's gone?

317
00:19:37,709 --> 00:19:39,211
Hello? Hello?

318
00:19:41,630 --> 00:19:42,714
Hello?

319
00:19:43,715 --> 00:19:45,717
Anybody there?

320
00:19:46,218 --> 00:19:48,053
I'm sorry, sir, but it's all down.
All the lines.

321
00:19:48,053 --> 00:19:49,972
The storm's hitting the mainland
like a hammer.

322
00:19:49,972 --> 00:19:51,890
If you get it working,
come find me immediately.

323
00:19:52,391 --> 00:19:54,393
The marshals need to make
an important call.

324
00:19:54,893 --> 00:19:55,811
Yes, sir.

325
00:19:58,981 --> 00:20:01,984
Hello? Hello?

326
00:20:02,367 --> 00:20:04,319
CAWLEY: I'm afraid
I have evening rounds
in the wards,

327
00:20:04,319 --> 00:20:08,323
but I'll be having drinks and a cigar
at my house around 9:00,

328
00:20:08,323 --> 00:20:10,325
if you'd care to drop by.

329
00:20:10,325 --> 00:20:12,461
Good.
We can talk then, right?

330
00:20:14,963 --> 00:20:16,965
We have been talking, Marshal.

331
00:20:25,724 --> 00:20:29,228
(CLASSICAL MUSIC PLAYING)

332
00:20:31,730 --> 00:20:33,515
(WHISTLES)

333
00:20:33,515 --> 00:20:36,852
Gotta say, I'm thinking I got in the wrong 
line of public service.

334
00:20:36,852 --> 00:20:40,489
It is a little overwhelming.
It was constructed during
the Civil War,

335
00:20:40,489 --> 00:20:43,825
the same time as the military fort
housing Ward C.

336
00:20:50,666 --> 00:20:52,834
This is the original
commander's quarters.

337
00:20:53,335 --> 00:20:54,836
When Uncle Sam got the bill,

338
00:20:54,836 --> 00:20:56,838
the commander was court-martialed.

339
00:20:56,838 --> 00:20:58,840
I can see why.

340
00:20:58,840 --> 00:21:01,343
Nice music.
Who is that? Brahms?

341
00:21:02,344 --> 00:21:03,345
No.

342
00:21:12,020 --> 00:21:13,522
It's Mahler.

343
00:21:13,522 --> 00:21:15,557
NAEHRING:
Quite right, Marshal.

344
00:21:16,058 --> 00:21:17,059
CAWLEY: Forgive me, gentlemen.

345
00:21:17,059 --> 00:21:19,528
My colleague,
Dr. Jeremiah Naehring.

346
00:21:28,537 --> 00:21:31,039
Quartet for Piano and Strings
in A minor.

347
00:21:35,043 --> 00:21:36,411
Your poison, gentlemen?

348
00:21:36,411 --> 00:21:37,913
Rye, if you got it.

349
00:21:37,913 --> 00:21:39,414
Soda and ice, please.
Thanks.

350
00:21:39,414 --> 00:21:44,086
Oh? You don't indulge in alcohol?
I'm surprised.

351
00:21:45,837 --> 00:21:49,758
Isn't it common for men in your profession
to imbibe?

352
00:21:49,758 --> 00:21:52,260
Common enough.
And yours?

353
00:21:54,229 --> 00:21:55,230
I'm sorry?

354
00:21:55,230 --> 00:21:57,265
Your profession, Doctor.
Psychiatry.

355
00:21:57,265 --> 00:21:58,767
Yes.

356
00:21:58,767 --> 00:22:00,569
I always heard it was overrun with 
boozers and drunks

357
00:22:00,569 --> 00:22:01,687
(CHUCKLES)

358
00:22:03,021 --> 00:22:05,774
Not that I've noticed.

359
00:22:05,774 --> 00:22:07,576
What's that? Iced tea in
your glass, there?

360
00:22:07,576 --> 00:22:09,027
(DOCTORS LAUGHING)

361
00:22:09,027 --> 00:22:14,333
Excellent, Marshal. You have outstanding
defense mechanisms.

362
00:22:14,333 --> 00:22:18,337
You must be quite adept
at interrogations, hmm?

363
00:22:26,011 --> 00:22:29,848
Men like you are
my specialty, you know?

364
00:22:30,349 --> 00:22:31,850
Men of violence.

365
00:22:32,351 --> 00:22:33,802
Now that's a hell of an assumption
to make.

366
00:22:34,302 --> 00:22:36,855
No assumption. No, not at all.
You misunderstand me.

367
00:22:36,855 --> 00:22:39,858
I said you are men of violence.

368
00:22:39,858 --> 00:22:42,861
I'm not accusing you of being violent men.

369
00:22:43,362 --> 00:22:44,363
That's quite different.

370
00:22:44,363 --> 00:22:46,982
No, please. Please
. Edify us, Doctor.

371
00:22:49,818 --> 00:22:51,820
You both
served overseas, huh?

372
00:22:51,820 --> 00:22:53,321
It's not much of a stretch, Doc.

373
00:22:53,321 --> 00:22:56,708
For all you know, we were both paper
pushers over there.

374
00:22:56,708 --> 00:22:58,076
No, you were not.

375
00:23:14,509 --> 00:23:15,761
Since the schoolyard,

376
00:23:15,761 --> 00:23:19,264
neither of you has ever walked away
from a physical conflict.

377
00:23:19,765 --> 00:23:21,767
No, no,
not because you enjoy it,

378
00:23:21,767 --> 00:23:25,854
but because retreat isn't something
you consider an option.

379
00:23:25,854 --> 00:23:27,355
We weren't raised to run, Doc.

380
00:23:27,856 --> 00:23:31,159
Ah! Yes. "Raised."

381
00:23:33,161 --> 00:23:35,163
And who raised you, Marshal?

382
00:23:35,614 --> 00:23:37,115
Me?

383
00:23:38,116 --> 00:23:39,918
Wolves. Ah!

384
00:23:39,918 --> 00:23:42,954
(DOCTORS LAUGHING)

385
00:23:42,954 --> 00:23:45,257
Very impressive defense mechanisms.

386
00:24:44,733 --> 00:24:46,434
NAEHRING: Do you
believe in God, Marshal?

387
00:24:50,739 --> 00:24:51,740
(CHUCKLES)

388
00:24:52,574 --> 00:24:54,526
No, I'm quite serious.

389
00:24:57,028 --> 00:24:59,331
(MUTTERS IN GERMAN)

390
00:25:00,749 --> 00:25:03,251
You ever seen a death camp, Doctor?

391
00:25:05,453 --> 00:25:07,756
(REPEATS IN GERMAN)

392
00:25:08,256 --> 00:25:09,257
Huh?

393
00:25:10,258 --> 00:25:14,763
(CONTINUES IN GERMAN)

394
00:25:18,717 --> 00:25:20,552
His English really is very good.

395
00:25:20,552 --> 00:25:23,471
You hit the consonants
a tad hard, though.

396
00:25:24,472 --> 00:25:27,192
You're a German?

397
00:25:27,192 --> 00:25:29,477
Is legal immigration a crime, Marshal?

398
00:25:29,477 --> 00:25:31,863
Oh, I don't know, Doctor.
You tell us.

399
00:25:34,366 --> 00:25:35,200
Now, listen.

400
00:25:35,700 --> 00:25:37,202
We're gonna need
those files on Sheehan

401
00:25:37,652 --> 00:25:39,154
and the rest of the staff as well.

402
00:25:39,154 --> 00:25:42,374
No personnel files will be
released to you. Period.

403
00:25:42,374 --> 00:25:44,209
(FIRMLY) We're gonna
need those files.

404
00:25:44,209 --> 00:25:45,460
Out of the question.

405
00:25:45,877 --> 00:25:47,212
Bullshit, out of the question!

406
00:25:47,212 --> 00:25:48,797
Bullshit!
(GLASS SHATTERING)

407
00:25:48,797 --> 00:25:51,249
Just who the hell's in charge here,
anyway, huh?

408
00:25:51,249 --> 00:25:55,053
Dr. Naehring acts as liaison to our
Board of Overseers.

409
00:25:55,053 --> 00:25:57,055
He relayed your request,
and it's been refused.

410
00:25:57,055 --> 00:25:59,257
Refused? They don't have the authority
to refuse,

411
00:25:59,758 --> 00:26:00,842
and neither do you, sir.

412
00:26:00,842 --> 00:26:02,510
Marshal, continue your investigation

413
00:26:03,011 --> 00:26:04,512
and we'll do all we can to help.

414
00:26:04,512 --> 00:26:06,097
.
This investigation is over

415
00:26:06,097 --> 00:26:08,400
We're gonna file our reports
and we're gonna hand it over to...

416
00:26:08,400 --> 00:26:09,601
CHUCK: Hoover's boys.

417
00:26:09,601 --> 00:26:10,986
Hoover's boys.
That's right.

418
00:26:10,986 --> 00:26:13,488
We'll be taking the ferry back
in the morning

419
00:26:13,488 --> 00:26:14,773
.
Come on, Chuck

420
00:26:23,448 --> 00:26:24,950
McPHERSON: Nice night.

421
00:26:30,705 --> 00:26:33,625
.
You'll be bunking
in the orderlies' quarters

422
00:26:45,470 --> 00:26:47,639
Hey, boss.

423
00:26:47,639 --> 00:26:49,641
We really packing it in?

424
00:26:50,141 --> 00:26:52,143
Why?

425
00:26:52,143 --> 00:26:56,815
I guess... I don't know,
I just never really quit anything before.

426
00:26:56,815 --> 00:27:00,201
We haven't heard the truth
once yet, Chuck.

427
00:27:00,201 --> 00:27:03,905
Listen, Rachel Solando didn't slip out 
of a locked cell, barefoot,

428
00:27:03,905 --> 00:27:05,407
without any help.

429
00:27:06,408 --> 00:27:08,743
I think she had a lot of help. 

430
00:27:09,244 --> 00:27:11,579
Maybe Cawley's sitting up
in his mansion right now

431
00:27:11,579 --> 00:27:13,882
rethinking his whole attitude.

432
00:27:15,333 --> 00:27:16,217
Maybe, in the morning,
we'll be...

433
00:27:16,217 --> 00:27:18,970
You're bluffing?

434
00:27:18,970 --> 00:27:21,006
I didn't say that.

435
00:27:31,733 --> 00:27:37,489
(EARLY 1950s
ROCK 'N' ROLL PLAYING)

436
00:27:39,491 --> 00:27:42,360
I found a whole stack of these, Teddy.

437
00:27:42,360 --> 00:27:45,113
Jesus, are you ever sober anymore?

438
00:27:46,114 --> 00:27:48,616
I killed a lot of people in the war.

439
00:27:50,618 --> 00:27:52,420
Is that why you drink?

440
00:27:55,340 --> 00:27:56,841
Are you real?

441
00:27:57,876 --> 00:27:58,877
No.

442
00:28:03,264 --> 00:28:04,599
She's still here.

443
00:28:05,517 --> 00:28:06,518
Who?

444
00:28:07,519 --> 00:28:08,887
Rachel?

445
00:28:10,388 --> 00:28:11,890
She never left.

446
00:28:25,570 --> 00:28:29,491
Remember when we stayed in the cabin
in the summer, Teddy?

447
00:28:29,991 --> 00:28:31,826
We were so happy.

448
00:28:34,329 --> 00:28:35,964
She's here.

449
00:28:35,964 --> 00:28:37,716
You can't leave.

450
00:28:50,478 --> 00:28:52,480
I'm not gonna leave.

451
00:28:53,982 --> 00:28:55,483
I love you so much.

452
00:29:00,271 --> 00:29:02,657
I'm just bones in a box, Teddy.

453
00:29:02,657 --> 00:29:03,658
No.

454
00:29:05,660 --> 00:29:06,661
I am.

455
00:29:09,748 --> 00:29:11,699
You have to wake up.

456
00:29:13,618 --> 00:29:15,120
I won't go.

457
00:29:15,754 --> 00:29:17,255
You're here.

458
00:29:19,257 --> 00:29:23,261
I'm not.
You have to face that.

459
00:29:26,264 --> 00:29:27,766
But she is.

460
00:29:30,268 --> 00:29:31,770
So is he.

461
00:29:33,772 --> 00:29:34,773
Who?

462
00:29:37,192 --> 00:29:38,693
Laeddis.

463
00:29:43,198 --> 00:29:44,699
I have to go.

464
00:29:44,699 --> 00:29:46,201
No.

465
00:29:46,201 --> 00:29:50,705
No, please. Please.
I need to hold on to you.

466
00:29:50,705 --> 00:29:52,207
Just a little bit longer, please.

467
00:29:52,207 --> 00:29:53,541
(GROANING) Oh, God, Teddy.

468
00:29:53,541 --> 00:29:55,543
You have to let me go.

469
00:29:55,543 --> 00:29:57,045
(SOBBING QUIETLY)

470
00:29:57,045 --> 00:29:58,546
I can't.

471
00:30:17,182 --> 00:30:18,600
(GASPS)

472
00:30:30,495 --> 00:30:32,497
Ain't gonna be no ferry in this shit.

473
00:30:37,452 --> 00:30:38,953
Doctor!

474
00:30:38,953 --> 00:30:40,955
Doctor, Doctor.

475
00:30:40,955 --> 00:30:41,956
We need to interview
the patients

476
00:30:42,457 --> 00:30:43,958
who were in Rachel's
group therapy session.

477
00:30:43,958 --> 00:30:45,960
I thought your investigation
was finished.

478
00:30:45,960 --> 00:30:48,796
Well, it's not like
we could take the ferry.

479
00:30:49,297 --> 00:30:52,467
Now, was Rachel receiving
any other treatments for her illnesses?

480
00:30:52,467 --> 00:30:53,768
(SIGHS)

481
00:30:54,269 --> 00:30:57,272
Do you know the state
of the mental health field
these days, gentlemen?

482
00:30:57,555 --> 00:30:59,474
.
No, not a clue, Doctor

483
00:30:59,474 --> 00:31:00,775
War.

484
00:31:01,192 --> 00:31:03,695
The old school believes
in surgical intervention.

485
00:31:03,695 --> 00:31:05,196
Psychosurgery.

486
00:31:05,196 --> 00:31:09,567
Procedures like
the transorbital lobotomy.

487
00:31:09,567 --> 00:31:12,570
Some say the patients
become reasonable, docile.

488
00:31:13,071 --> 00:31:15,373
Others say they
become zombies.

489
00:31:15,373 --> 00:31:16,157
And the new school?

490
00:31:16,157 --> 00:31:17,625
Psychopharmacology.

491
00:31:17,625 --> 00:31:19,627
A new drug has just been approved
called Thorazine,

492
00:31:19,627 --> 00:31:22,997
which relaxes psychotic patients,
you could say tames them.

493
00:31:22,997 --> 00:31:24,499
And which school are you, Doctor?

494
00:31:24,499 --> 00:31:26,000
Me?

495
00:31:26,000 --> 00:31:28,920
I have this radical idea that if you treat a patient
with respect,

496
00:31:28,920 --> 00:31:33,424
listen to him, try and understand,
you just might reach him.

497
00:31:33,925 --> 00:31:36,060
(WOMAN SCREAMING)

498
00:31:36,060 --> 00:31:39,063
Come on, Marge
. It's okay.

499
00:31:40,064 --> 00:31:41,065
These patients, huh?

500
00:31:41,065 --> 00:31:42,767
Even these.

501
00:31:42,767 --> 00:31:44,769
What should be a last resort is becoming
a first response.

502
00:31:44,769 --> 00:31:48,489
Give them a pill, put them in a corner,
it all goes away.

503
00:31:48,489 --> 00:31:50,992
Rachel Solando was
on a combination of drugs

504
00:31:50,992 --> 00:31:52,994
meant to keep her
from becoming violent,

505
00:31:52,994 --> 00:31:55,863
but it was only
intermittently effective.

506
00:31:56,331 --> 00:31:57,832
The greatest obstacle
to her recovery

507
00:31:57,832 --> 00:32:00,835
was her refusal to face
what she had done.

508
00:32:01,836 --> 00:32:03,421
"Was."

509
00:32:03,421 --> 00:32:05,423
Is there a reason you keep referring
to your patient

510
00:32:05,924 --> 00:32:08,426
in the past tense, Doctor?

511
00:32:10,929 --> 00:32:14,432
Look outside, Marshal.
Why do you think?

512
00:32:21,639 --> 00:32:23,191
Next up is Peter Breene.

513
00:32:23,191 --> 00:32:25,193
